Bikeshare Demand Forecast¶

by Simon Park, 2/8/2020¶

Goal: forecast bike rental demand in the Capital Bikeshare program in Washington D.C.

Variable Importance¶

In this section, we provide the reasoning behind our selection of variables and the logic behind data transformations we made, if any.

Year / Month / Day / Hour / Daylabel¶

In [5]:

Out[5]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1ba67bc55c8>

year

  • 2012 has higher demand than 2011. This is because the company is growing, as illustrated in daylabel column.

month

  • The demand is concentrated on June to August. There is a noticeble drop in demand during December to Februrary.
  • However, notice that December has twice as much demand compared to Janurary.
    • This variable is further inspected in the later section. (spoiler: will be dropped)

day

  • The training data only contains day 1 to 19 of each month, while the test data contains day 20 and onward. We believe this is susceptible to overfitting the data.
    • This variable is dropped in our specification.

hour

  • The demand generally is high during the daytime and low during the nighttime.
  • There are two peaks: 7 to 9 and 16 to 19, which are rush hours.
    • This variable is further inspected in the later section.

daylabel

  • This column, at a first glance, contains the largest amount of information.
  • Especially, above plot illustrates seasonal temporal trend.
    • This variable is further inspected in the later section. (spoiler: it will be transformed)
In [6]:
train["year_month"] = train["year"].astype('str') + "-" + train["month"].astype('str')

figure, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)
figure.set_size_inches(14, 5)

sns.barplot(data=train, x="year", y="count", ax=ax1)
sns.barplot(data=train, x="month", y="count", ax=ax2)

figure, ax3 = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1)
figure.set_size_inches(14, 5)

sns.barplot(data=train, x="year_month", y="count", ax=ax3)

train = train.drop("year_month", axis=1)

This clearly tells us that the reason December has a doublefold demand is 1) the company is growing; and 2) the data is available from 2011-1 to 2012-12, i.e. December has higher demand due to the growth. We believe that this is also susceptible to overfitting. We have an option to use one-hot key encoding on year_month variable to deal with this issue in theory. However, factors do not work with XGboost very well and therefore we instead drop month column to prevent overfitting.

Out[8]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1ba69d62608>

The above plots show that

  • the demand is high during rush hours: 7 to 9 and 16 to 19.
  • but the pattern is limited to weekdays (workingday == 1). On weekends, the demand is high in the afternoon (10 to 16) rather than the rush hours.
  • The same behavior is observed during holidays (holiday == 0).

To address this finding and exploit the information, we created a new variable dayofweek:

  • 1-Saturday, 2-Sunday, 3-Monday, 4-Tuesday, 5-Wednesday, 6-Thursday, 7-Friday.
  • Notice that daily patterns follow the above findings, but also illustrates differences as well, such as lower demand on Fridays during the evening and lower demand on Sundays compared to Saturdays.
  • We expect this variable to
    1. offset some of the information loss caused by excluding day column and;
    2. carry all the information that was valuable in daylabel column.

The above plot shows one day in the training data with weird atemp record and another day with abnormal humidity.

We find the days that are odd in each variable and report them above, respectively. We find

  1. daylabel=595 reports atemp=12.12 for every hour recorded that day, which is obviously a recording mistake given that temp varies.
  2. daylabel=69: reports humidity=0.0 for every hour recorded that day, which again can be seen an obvious recording mistake.

However, the observations do contain valuable information in other columns and after trial-and-error (with results that are not reported in this document) we decide to keep the observations.

It appears that count has a skewed distribution as it is highly concentrated on 0-20 counts and streatches out to nearly 1000 counts. To mitigate the issue, we implement log transformation to make underlying distribution resemble gaussian distribution.

Notice that we need to convert log_count back after making predictions, which is illustrated on rev_count using exponential transformation.

Evaluation Standards¶

In this section, we develop a scorer function based on our evaluation standards.

Predictions will be evaluated using the root mean squared error (RMSE), calculated as $$ \text{RMSE} \equiv \sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (p_i - a_i)^2 } $$

where $a_i$ is the true count (actual), $p_i$ is the estimate (prediction), and $n$ is the number of entries to be evaluated.

In [20]:
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer

def rmse(predict, actual):
    p = np.array(predict)
    a = np.array(actual)
    e = predict - actual
    se = e ** 2
    mse = se.mean()
    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
    return rmse

rmse_scorer = make_scorer(rmse)
rmse_scorer
Out[20]:
make_scorer(rmse)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

In this section, we tune our GBM hyperparameters using XGboost and sklearn modules.

(Note) this section is very costly and thus the computation takes a long time. For that reason, the best hyperparmeters are saved below for reproducibility.

In [21]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
import xgboost as xgb
xgb.XGBRegressor()
Out[21]:
XGBRegressor(base_score=0.5, booster='gbtree', colsample_bylevel=1,
             colsample_bynode=1, colsample_bytree=1, gamma=0,
             importance_type='gain', learning_rate=0.1, max_delta_step=0,
             max_depth=3, min_child_weight=1, missing=None, n_estimators=100,
             n_jobs=1, nthread=None, objective='reg:linear', random_state=0,
             reg_alpha=0, reg_lambda=1, scale_pos_weight=1, seed=None,
             silent=None, subsample=1, verbosity=1)

The parameters that we look for include:

  • n_estimators: denotes the number of trees.
  • max_depth: used to control over-fitting as higher depth will allow model to learn relations very specific to a particular sample.
  • learning_rate: makes the model more robust by shrinking the weights on each step.
  • subsample: denotes the fraction of observations to be randomly samples for each tree.
  • colsample_bytree: denotes the fraction of columns to be randomly samples for each tree.
  • colsample_bylevel: denotes the subsample ratio of columns for each split, in each level.

We run a 10-fold CV.

In [ ]:
coarse_hyperparam_list = []
for search in range(100):
    n_estimators = np.random.randint(low=100, high=1000)
    max_depth = np.random.randint(low=2, high=100)
    learning_rate = 10 ** -np.random.uniform(low=0, high=2)
    subsample = np.random.uniform(low=0.1, high=1.0)
    colsample_bytree = np.random.uniform(low=0.3, high=1.0)
    colsample_bylevel = np.random.uniform(low=0.3, high=1.0)

    model = xgb.XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror',
                             n_estimators=n_estimators,
                             max_depth=max_depth,
                             learning_rate=learning_rate,
                             subsample=subsample,
                             colsample_bylevel=colsample_bylevel,
                             colsample_bytree=colsample_bytree,
                             seed=37)

    score = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring=rmse_scorer).mean()
    
    hyperparameters = {
        'search': search,
        'score': score,
        'n_estimators': n_estimators,
        'max_depth': max_depth,
        'learning_rate': learning_rate,
        'subsample': subsample,
        'colsample_bylevel': colsample_bylevel,
        'colsample_bytree': colsample_bytree,
    }
    coarse_hyperparam_list.append(hyperparameters)
    print(f"{search:2} n_estimators = {n_estimators}, max_depth = {max_depth:2}, learning_rate = {learning_rate:.10f}, subsample = {subsample:.6f}, colsample_bylevel = {colsample_bylevel:.6f}, colsample_bytree = {colsample_bytree:.6f}, Score = {score:.5f}")

coarse_hyperparam_list = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(coarse_hyperparam_list)
coarse_hyperparam_list = coarse_hyperparam_list.sort_values(by="score")
print(coarse_hyperparam_list.shape)
coarse_hyperparam_list.head(5)

After the coarse search, we retrieve min-max range of the hyperparameters and execute another random search, a finer search.

  • n_estimators = 300 ~ 1,000
  • max_depth = 2 ~ 60
  • learning_rate = 1.0 ~ 0.01
  • subsample = 0.2 ~ 0.7
  • colsample_bytree = 0.7 ~ 1.0
  • colsample_bylevel = 0.4 ~ 1.0

This time, we run a 20-fold CV.

In [ ]:
finer_hyperparam_list = []
for search in range(100):
    n_estimators = np.random.randint(low=300, high=1000)
    max_depth = np.random.randint(low=2, high=30)
    learning_rate = 10 ** -np.random.uniform(low=0, high=2)
    subsample = np.random.uniform(low=0.2, high=0.7)
    colsample_bytree = np.random.uniform(low=0.7, high=1.0)
    colsample_bylevel = np.random.uniform(low=0.4, high=1.0)

    model = xgb.XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror',
                             n_estimators=n_estimators,
                             max_depth=max_depth,
                             learning_rate=learning_rate,
                             subsample=subsample,
                             colsample_bylevel=colsample_bylevel,
                             colsample_bytree=colsample_bytree,
                             seed=37)

    score = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=20, scoring=rmse_scorer).mean()

        'search': search,
        'score': score,
        'n_estimators': n_estimators,
        'max_depth': max_depth,
        'learning_rate': learning_rate,

        'colsample_bylevel': colsample_bylevel,
        'colsample_bytree': colsample_bytree,

Gradient Boosting Machine¶

GBM Gradient Boosting Machine) is known to have best perform for structured data, one of the most powerful machine learning algorithms. Therefore we use GBM, using XGBRegressor from XGBoost model. We define our medel with the best hyperparameters.
